National Security Advisor Jake Sullivan recently met with his counterparts from South Korea and Japan for the fourth trilateral meeting of the Biden-Harris Administration. They discussed various initiatives, including regional crises, ballistic missile defense data sharing, and addressing North Korea's use of cryptocurrency for illicit programs. They also talked about economic security, supply chain early warning, and aligning Indo-Pacific strategies. They agreed to counter the deepening partnership between North Korea and Russia and emphasized the importance of peace and stability in the Taiwan Straits and freedom of navigation in the South China Sea and East China Sea. Sullivan expressed gratitude for South Korea and Japan's commitment to Ukraine and praised their efforts to strengthen bilateral ties.